    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Ambitious' Women</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Amy Richards letter questions New York State Republican Party chmn William Powers's characterization of Hillary Rodham Clinton as 'ambitious woman' who should be stopped from 'fooling voters'; asks since when has ambition been a negative?</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Maureen Dowd (column, Sept. 20) says that William Powers, the New York State Republican Party chairman, characterized Hillary Rodham Clinton in a fund-raising letter as an ''ambitious'' woman who should be stopped ''from fooling voters.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Maureen Dowd (column, Sept. 20) says that William Powers, the New York State Republican Party chairman, characterized Hillary Rodham Clinton in a fund-raising letter as an ''ambitious'' woman who should be stopped ''from fooling voters.''</p>
        <p>Since when has ambition been a negative, especially in New York? Or is it just a negative for women?</p>
        <p>AMY RICHARDS  Pasadena, Calif., Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
